<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="55" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,665,762,825]" box="[151,302,799,825]" pageId="16" pageNumber="55">
(
<figureCitation box="[159,294,799,825]" captionStart="FIGURES 27–28" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1556,1580]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1065,1533]" captionTargetId="figure-313@16.[151,1436,1065,1533]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 27–28. Paragrallomyia ecuadoriensis n. sp. 27, female, dorsal view; 28, female internal reproductive structures, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4401216" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4401216/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="55">Figs. 27–28</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,871,1041]" pageId="16" pageNumber="55">
Description (female only): Body length 
<quantity box="[607,677,871,897]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="16" pageNumber="55" unit="mm" value="6.0">6 mm</quantity>
; wing 
<quantity box="[754,824,871,897]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="16" pageNumber="55" unit="mm" value="4.0">4 mm</quantity>
. Head brown, thorax black and abdomen dark brown. Palpus brown except for white outer face. Clypeus brown with sparse pale microsetulae. First flagellomere dark brown. Fronto-orbital plate yellowish-brown. Row of katepisternal setae brownish. Fore tibia dark brown. Fore tarsus mostly white, tarsomere one brown on basal half only. Hind femur mostly dark brown, white on basal quarter and with a small angled preapical white ring. Tergites dark brown. Oviscape dark brown.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4401216" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4401216" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4401216/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="55" startId="16.[151,264,1556,1580]" targetBox="[151,1436,1065,1533]" targetPageId="16">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1436,1556,1616]" pageId="16" pageNumber="55">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,342,1556,1580]" pageId="16" pageNumber="55">FIGURES 27–28.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Ferro &amp; Marshall, 2020" authorityName="Ferro &amp; Marshall" authorityYear="2020" box="[350,661,1556,1580]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Paragrallomyia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ecuadoriensis" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[350,661,1556,1580]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="55">Paragrallomyia ecuadoriensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[668,727,1556,1580]" pageId="16" pageNumber="55">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[668,727,1556,1580]" pageId="16" pageNumber="55" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
27, female, dorsal view; 28, female internal reproductive structures, ventral view.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1436,1662,2012]" pageId="16" pageNumber="55">
Head: First flagellomere covered by pale microsetulae. Frontal vitta uniformly brown, without a darkened spot anterior to ocellar plate. Frontal vitta flat, not swollen anterior to ocellar plate. Epicephala converging, not immediately merging posterior to ocellar plate (
<figureCitation box="[601,685,1734,1761]" captionStart="FIGURES 27–28" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1556,1580]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1065,1533]" captionTargetId="figure-313@16.[151,1436,1065,1533]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 27–28. Paragrallomyia ecuadoriensis n. sp. 27, female, dorsal view; 28, female internal reproductive structures, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4401216" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4401216/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="55">Fig. 27</figureCitation>
). Epicephalon somewhat swollen above frontal vitta level.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1436,1662,2012]" pageId="16" pageNumber="55">
Thorax: Mesonotum with lines of thin brownish microsetulae. Anterior half of postpronotal lobe bare. Femur covered with sparse black microsetulae. Mid and hind tibia flattened, sulcus on outer face strongly pronounced and curved. Cervical sclerite brown with a rounded swelling. Cell r 
<subScript attach="left" box="[856,882,1861,1875]" fontSize="6" pageId="16" pageNumber="55">4+5</subScript>
open at the tip of the wing.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1436,1662,2012]" pageId="16" pageNumber="55">
Abdomen: Single spermathecal duct smooth and with a small swelling apically. Single spermatheca smooth and cylindrical. Paired spermathecal duct uniformly thick, with an apical rounded swelling. Paired spermathecal duct stems tapered on basal third, broader and convoluted on apical half (
<figureCitation box="[991,1077,1950,1977]" captionStart="FIGURES 27–28" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1556,1580]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1065,1533]" captionTargetId="figure-313@16.[151,1436,1065,1533]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 27–28. Paragrallomyia ecuadoriensis n. sp. 27, female, dorsal view; 28, female internal reproductive structures, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4401216" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4401216/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="55">Fig. 28</figureCitation>
). Paired spermathecae oval and smooth.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
