<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="56" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,150,393]" pageId="17" pageNumber="56">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,338,330,356]" pageId="17" pageNumber="56">Comments:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ferro &amp; Marshall" authorityYear="2020" box="[344,527,330,356]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Paragrallomyia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ecuadoriensis">
<emphasis box="[344,527,330,356]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="56">P. ecuadoriensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ferro &amp; Marshall" authorityYear="2020" box="[671,773,331,356]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Paragrallomyia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="citrina">
<emphasis box="[671,773,331,356]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="56">P. citrina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but its mid and hind tibiae are conspicuously flattened and curved. The thick and twisted paired spermathecal duct stems also make this species distinct.
</paragraph>
